revision.text:
'''Raiden Shrine''' (雷電神社, Raiden Jinja) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Kazo, Saitama|ja|加須市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Saitama Prefecture. It enshrines {{ill|Kamo-wake-ikazuchi|ja|賀茂別雷命|12=draft|12=draft}} and is classified as a former [[Son-sha]] under the Modern Shrine Ranking System.
== History == The exact date of the shrine's founding is unknown. According to oral tradition, the shrine was originally located to the north of the estate of the Kadoi family, an old local family. As the estate expanded, the shrine was relocated to a nearby hilltop. The neighboring {{ill|Jōtai-ji|ja|定泰寺|12=draft|12=draft}} served as the shrine's {{ill|bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|12=draft|12=draft}} (managing temple).<ref name="jinja">Saitama Prefecture Shrine Research Group, ''Saitama no Jinja: Iruma, Kita Saitama, Chichibu,'' Saitama Shrine Bureau, 1986, pp. 922–923.</ref>
In 1872, under the {{ill|Modern System of Ranked Shinto Shrines|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=draft|12=draft}}, Raiden Shrine was ranked as a "Village Shrine" (村社). During the {{ill|Shrine Consolidation Policy|ja|神社合祀|1=Shrine Consolidation Policy|12=draft|12=draft}}, three surrounding shrines were merged into Raiden Shrine in 1908. In 1909, the shrine also absorbed {{ill|Shinmei Shrine|ja|神明社|12=draft|12=draft}} and its associated shrines.<ref name="jinja"></ref>
== Cultural Properties == * '''Lion Dance of Minami-Ōkuwa''' (南大桑の獅子舞) – This traditional lion dance is designated as an Intangible Folk Cultural Property by {{ill|Kazo|ja|加須市|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was officially recognized on September 8, 1960.<ref name="city">[https://www.city.kazo.lg.jp/soshiki/shougai/kankou/kazochiiki/6497.html Kazo Area Designated Cultural Properties], Kazo City.</ref>
== Access == * Approximately 25 minutes on foot from {{ill|Hanazaki Station|ja|花崎駅|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== References == {{reflist}}
== Bibliography == * Saitama Prefecture Shrine Research Group, ''Saitama no Jinja: Iruma, Kita Saitama, Chichibu,'' Saitama Shrine Bureau, 1986.
