== History == The exact date of the shrine's founding is unknown. According to oral tradition, the shrine was originally located to the north of the estate of the Kadoi family, an old local family. As the estate expanded, the shrine was relocated to a nearby hilltop. The neighboring {{ill|Jōtai-ji|ja|定泰寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōtai-ji|qq=}} served as the shrine's {{ill|bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bettō-ji|qq=}} (managing temple).<ref name="jinja">Saitama Prefecture Shrine Research Group, ''Saitama no Jinja: Iruma, Kita Saitama, Chichibu,'' Saitama Shrine Bureau, 1986, pp. 922–923.</ref>
In 1872, under the [[:en:Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]], Raiden Shrine was Ranked as a "Village Shrine" (村社). During the [[:en:Shrine Consolidation Policy|Shrine Consolidation Policy]], three surrounding shrines were merged into Raiden Shrine in 1908. In 1909, the shrine also absorbed {{ill|Shinmei Shrine|ja|神明社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinmei Shrine|qq=}} and its associated shrines.<ref name="jinja"></ref>
== Cultural Properties == * '''Lion Dance of Minami-Ōkuwa''' (南大桑の獅子舞) – This traditional lion dance is designated as an Intangible Folk Cultural Property by [[:en:Kazo, Saitama|Kazo]]. It was officially recognized on September 8, 1960.<ref name="city">[https://www.city.kazo.lg.jp/soshiki/shougai/kankou/kazochiiki/6497.html Kazo Area Designated Cultural Properties], Kazo City.</ref>
== Access == * Approximately 25 minutes on foot from [[:en:Hanasaki Station (Saitama)|Hanazaki Station]].
